  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex transactions or legitimate businesses. Key elements typically include:\n\n1. Placement stage:\n- Introducing illegal funds into financial system\n- Converting cash into financial instruments\n- Depositing funds into bank accounts\n\n2. Layering stage:\n- Creating complex financial transactions\n- Obscuring the money's original source\n- Transferring funds between multiple accounts\n\n3. Integration stage:\n- Reintroducing laundered funds into legitimate economy\n- Making illegal money appear legal and usable\n\nLegal definitions vary by jurisdiction, but generally require:\n- Intentional concealment of illegal funds\n- Knowledge that money originates from criminal activity\n- Deliberate attempts to disguise money's origin\n\nSpecific legal definitions exist in:\n- U.S. Bank Secrecy Act\n- International Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Individual countries' criminal codes\n\nCommon predicate crimes include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Illegal gambling\n- Terrorist financing\n\nPenalties typically involve significant fines and potential imprisonment.\n\nNote: This is general information and shouldn't be considered legal advice.",
